DECISION: Map Structure — City Stages as Run Progression System

The run layer and city layer share the same map. The player is always 
in their city. The street layout, road routing, and core four buildings 
(Lab, Gym, Tailor Shop, Lair) are consistent landmarks across all stages 
and recognizable within the run layer.

The city develops through four visual stages. Each stage is mechanically 
a distinct run environment — different enemy density, different challenges, 
different difficulty — layered on top of the same underlying street 
geography. City development is simultaneously the game's visual progression 
system and its difficulty and map progression system.

STAGE ONE — Rundown. Tutorial environment. Constrained geography, limited 
complexity. One mission type available per tutorial run, heavily nudged 
by world broadcasts. Lowest difficulty.

STAGE TWO — Developing. Mid-game. All three mission types available 
simultaneously. Increasing enemy density and challenge. City visibly 
recovering.

STAGE THREE — Refined. Late mid-game. Full mechanical complexity unlocked. 
All systems active. Higher difficulty. City approaching modern.

STAGE FOUR — Modern. Endless live game tail. Full sandbox. Rex Flynn 
modifiers create run-specific public challenges. Procedurally generated 
missions and bosses ensure no two runs are identical. Maximum difficulty 
and maximum replayability. Designed to sustain indefinite play beyond 
the structured progression arc.

Cosmetic city development changes do not need to propagate granularly 
into the run layer beyond the stage-level visual identity shift.

DATE: May 5, 2026

WHY: Sharing the same street map across all stages creates spatial memory 
and narrative coherence. Using visual stage development as the difficulty 
and map progression system means city growth does double duty — rewarding 
progression and raising stakes simultaneously. Stage four as a procedurally 
generated endless sandbox ensures the game has a live game tail without 
requiring separate mode development.

