DECISION: Run Time Structure and Mission Reveal Model

A single run is 20 minutes, structured in three acts:

ACT ONE — Prep Period (0-5 minutes)
Mission locations are hidden. The player builds their loadout through 
milestone-based power selections. Movement through the city is open 
but carries risk — stumbling into a mission location before the prep 
period ends makes that mission live immediately, whether the player 
is ready or not.

ACT TWO — Open Window (5-15 minutes)
All three mission locations reveal simultaneously on the map. Players 
can see what's available and continue building toward their preferred 
mission type. Full player agency — attempt a mission immediately or 
keep developing the loadout.

ACT THREE — Forced Commitment (15-20 minutes)
At 15 minutes the game forces a mission choice. Whatever the player 
has built is what they take in. Five minutes to execute. Success or 
failure resolves here.

Mission locations are randomized each run — no mission type has a fixed 
geographic location. Locations are visible once revealed and can be 
stumbled upon before reveal during the prep period. This creates narrative 
variety and prevents staleness.

DATE: May 5, 2026

WHY: 20 minutes is substantial enough to feel meaningful and short enough 
to sustain a one-more-run impulse. The three act structure gives every 
run dramatic shape. The forced choice at 15 minutes ensures build decisions 
carry weight. Randomized mission locations support narrative variety and 
prevent the world from feeling scripted or repetitive.

REPLACES: Nothing — new decision

