DECISION: Class Mentor System — Framework and Introduction Triggers

Each of the four classes has a corresponding mentor character who occupies 
a class-specific building in the city. These buildings exist from early 
progression but appear non-descript until the mentor relationship unlocks. 
At unlock the building reveals what it actually is — hidden in plain sight. 
The reveal rewards city exploration and creates a world that feels deeper 
the more the player progresses.

Mentor relationships unlock through class progression and playtime. 
Each introduction is native to its class — tonally and mechanically 
distinct — and functions as a three-panel comic book moment in its 
own right.

BRAWLER MENTOR — Like recognizes like.
The mentor sees the player fight from across the street and walks over. 
No mysticism, no technology. A veteran fighter who knows what they're 
looking at. Direct, physical, slightly gruff. The introduction is the 
first lesson — they have an opinion about your form before a word 
of welcome.

SPEEDSTER MENTOR — Sense the presence of another.
Attuned in ways that aren't entirely explainable, the mentor finds 
the player before the player finds them. Already standing nearby when 
the player turns around. The player didn't hear them arrive. They don't 
know how long they've been there.

TACTICIAN MENTOR — Tech detects tech.
The player's equipment flags the mentor's technology as a threat and 
generates a danger alert. The player investigates expecting an enemy 
and finds a person — someone whose equipment makes the player's look 
like a prototype. Adversarial before collaborative. The mentor was 
expecting the alert. It was deliberate.

BLASTER MENTOR — The city reacts.
Lights flicker and die in sequence across two city blocks. Electronics 
glitch. The player investigates the anomaly and finds a person at the 
center of it — someone who has been living with uncontrolled energy 
output for years and has mastered it. They recognized the player's 
energy signature from six blocks away. The blackout was not an accident.

MENTOR NARRATIVE FUNCTION:
Each mentor provides narrative justification for why advanced class 
powers exist and are teachable. Mechanically, class mastery remains 
tied to run completion (10 successful runs for second tier, 30 for 
third tier). The mentor is the story of why the unlock happens — 
not the gate that controls it.

Mentor introductions are world events that generate content across 
all three feedback channels. Rex Flynn would cover the Eastside 
blackout. Citizens would have theories about the fighter who hangs 
around the old gym. The Superhero Community would have opinions about 
these mentors taking on an unknown hero.

DATE: May 5, 2026

WHY: The mentor system transforms class mastery unlocks from arbitrary 
progression gates into relationships with narrative weight. Each 
introduction is a comic book moment native to its class. The 
hidden-in-plain-sight building reveal rewards city exploration. 
Mentor introductions as world events connect the system organically 
to the existing feedback channels.

REPLACES: Nothing — new decision

